The '''West Virginia Folklore Society''' was an organization devoted to studying and collecting [[folklore]] in the United States, founded in 1913. It was among the most prominent such organizations in the early 20th century.<ref>[http://www.mustrad.org.uk/reviews/anthract.htm Musical Traditions]</ref>
[[John Harrington Cox]], archivist and editor for the West Virginia Folklore Society, published an influential collection of folk songs in 1925, called ''Folk-Songs of the South: Collected Under the Auspices of the West Virginia Folk-Lore Society''.<ref>Crawford, pg. 604</ref> Cox had founded the society with WVU vice-president Robert Armstrong and Walter Barnes of [[Fairmont Normal School]].<ref>Tribe, pgs. 9-10</ref>
